This repository documents the step-by-step process I use to install Kali Linux and Ubuntu on Oracle VirtualBox.
It also includes system requirements, configurations, and troubleshooting steps I encountered.

Prerequisites
Before installation, ensure you have:
-Oracle VirtualBox installed
-VirtualBox Extension Pack
-At least 8 GB RAM (recommended)
-50 GB free disk space
-ISO / Pre-built VM files downloaded

Kali Linux installation steps
-Visit the official Kali Linux page and download the VirtualBox image. After unzipping the file, there are .vbox, .vdi, and .vbox files. I will be using the .vdi file.

VirtualBox
- Click New in VirtualBox
- Name: Kali Linux
- Type: Linux/ Version: Debian (64-bit)
- Memory: Set to at least 2048mb
- Har disk: This is the crucial step: Select "use an existing virtual hard disk file."
- Link the. Vdi file:
   * Click the small folder icon next to the drop-down menu
   * Click add at the top
   * Navigate into your kali-linux.2025.4-virtualbox-amd64 folder
   * Select the file ending with .vdi
   * Click Open the choose, and finally create.

Before starting your machine, always go back and look at your system settings, adjust where you feel some adjustments are needed.

Ubuntu Installation
Download Ubuntu ISO
Download Ubuntu Desktop LTS ISO from the official website

Create New Virtual Machine
Open VirtualBox
Click New
Name: Ubuntu
Type: Linux
Version: Ubuntu (64-bit)

Allocate Resources
Recommended:
RAM: 4096 MB
CPU: 2 processors
Disk: 25–50 GB (VDI, Dynamically allocated)

Attach ISO File
Go to Settings → Storage
Under Controller IDE → Add ISO
Select the Ubuntu ISO file

Start Installation
Click Start
Select Install Ubuntu
Choose:
Keyboard layout
Normal installation
Erase disk & install Ubuntu (Virtual disk only)

Create User Account
Set:
Username
Password
Computer name

Complete Installation
Wait for the installation to finish
Restart VM
Remove ISO when prompted


      


